<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54144a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54144a">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54144a"> 144(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> prays to Mts</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&laquo;Il est de notori&eacute;t&eacute; publique chez les Canaques, &eacute;crit M. Leenhardt, qu&apos;on ne priait point autrefois les dieux, on priait leur habitat. On disait le nom des montagnes ou des lieux g&eacute;ographiques int&eacute;ressants&mdash;grande pi&egrave;ce d&apos;eau, &eacute;boulis de rochers (ceux-ci jouent un grand r&ocirc;le &agrave; cause de l&apos;humidit&eacute; qu&apos;ils comportent). On s&apos;adressait &agrave; celui qui paraissait le possesseur de ce. lieu, y repr&eacute;sentait la vie, et en &eacute;tait la. Personnification, le totem ou l&apos;anc&ecirc;tre. Nous avons pu noter, aupr&egrave;s de quelques vieillards, <mark>des pri&egrave;res aux montagnes</mark>. <br><font color="green">["It is common knowledge among the Canaques, writes Mr. Leenhardt, that the gods were not once prayed, their habitat was prayed. They said the names of mountains or interesting geographical places - large body of water, scree of rocks (these play a big role because of the humidity they contain). We were speaking to whoever appeared to be the owner of this. place, represented life there, and was there. Personification, the totem or the ancestor. We were able to note, with some old men, prayers to the mountains.]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 181</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
